{"title":"TASKNORM: Rethinking Batch Normalization for Meta-Learning","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Conventional batch normalization (BN) violates the hierarchical, task-specific i.i.d. assumptions of meta-learning: global running statistics (CBN/BRN) lead to poor accuracy (especially with small batches/few shots), while transductive BN (TBN) uses target-set statistics at test time, yielding brittle behavior and unfair advantages.","method":"Introduce Meta-Batch Normalization (METABN): compute batch moments from the task’s context set D_τ and use them to normalize both context and target examples at meta-train and meta-test time. This makes normalization task-local and non-transductive, aligning with the hierarchical model (µ,σ absorbed into ψ_τ). Empirically, METABN improves training speed while maintaining accuracy versus CBN/BRN, but suffers when |D_τ| is small due to high-variance moment estimates (e.g., Section 4.1; lines 145–149; Table 1 and discussion lines 205–209)."},{"problem":"A non-transductive normalization that remains accurate and efficient across varying, often small, context sizes is needed; METABN alone degrades with few-shot tasks, and TBN—while strong—depends transductively on the test batch and fails under streaming or class-imbalanced evaluation.","method":"Propose TASKNORM: blend task-level context-set BN moments with per-instance, non-transductive moments (from IN or LN) for each example using pooled mean/variance. A learnable blending factor α=SIGMOID(SCALE·|D_τ|+OFFSET) is trained, enabling each layer to adaptively weight context versus instance statistics as a function of context size. TASKNORM is non-transductive (uses only D_τ and the current x*), has variants TASKNORM-I/L (using IN/LN), and includes RN as a special case (fixed α=|D_τ|/(1+|D_τ|)). Experiments across 14 datasets and multiple meta-learners (MAML, ProtoNets, CNAPS) show TASKNORM consistently improves accuracy and training speed; on Meta-Dataset, TASKNORM-I attains the best average rank (e.g., CNAPS rank 2.38, ProtoNets 2.50) and often outperforms transductive TBN, while remaining robust when evaluated one example or one class at a time (Sections 4.2–5; lines 153–166, 191–193, 237–243, 283; Table 2–3; Table D.2)."}]}
